<h2 id="make-your-free-time-count">Make your free time count</h2>

<p>This exercise also forces me to look forward into my life and be really intentional with my calendar and inherently, my time. When retroactively filling in my calendar, I have that vantage point of my past few days which simultaneously helps me evaluate how I want to spend my upcoming days.</p>

<p>Speaking of productivity, I really didnâ€™t want this to tool to be a â€œproductivity hackâ€ or to use it to â€œoptimize my timeâ€. If anything, one could say that this is the opposite of optimal. Why look back so intently when that time could be used looking forward? Of course, everyone has their own definition of â€œoptimal.â€ For me, that sometimes means bettering myself in some way, working on a â€œside projectâ€ (gross), expanding my skills in a hobby, or filling the time with people by going out to concerts, restaurants or other activities a Toronto-based 20-something would partake in that are considered Instagram-able.</p>

